Got  it
If  user  set  key  but  the value  is  blank .  we  should  set a blank field  . 
If  user  set  key  and   the value  is not  blank .  we  should  override filed  . 
If user don't set property  , we don't  set the target field .

Let's  talk  about Map filed . if  I  declare my field in class as following 
```
private static Map<String,String > filed = new HashMap<String, String>() {
            {
                put("a", "1");
                put("b", "2");
            }
        };
```
Then I config  the property  like `XXXX.field[c]=3` in `agent.config` , Finally , I will  get  a  map  that contains `a ` ,`b`,`c` .
I think  we should't merge the initial  value and property value  , property value should override initial filed , Finally , I should  get  a  map  that  only contains `c`.


> This is by design. Things like `service name`, we do cutting it to follow the protocol requirement.

Let's log warn message , or throw an exception ?

> So, what would happen if I put an `endpoint` as a key in the JSON formated body? Is the JSON's endpoint or endpoint in the root field has higher priority?

Hi, it does nothing if you put an `endpoint`/`instance`/`service` in the json body, UNLESS users explicitly specify that this one should override the top-level `endpoint` (which is [defined in the protocol](https://github.com/apache/skywalking-data-collect-protocol/blob/906a834dc0c3fb66719b8313f8f9298be3a27349/logging/Logging.proto#L61) like this


```groovy
filter {
    // ...
    extractor {
        endpoint parsed.endpoint
    }
}
```

I find a bug about `abort{}`.
If there are 2 lal files : default.yaml and mysql-slowsql.yaml, and they are configured by
```
lalFiles: ${SW_LOG_LAL_FILES:mysql-slowsql,default}
```
The default.yaml will load before mysql-slowsql.yaml.
So if I send a json(layer = "MYSQL") to OAP, it will execute the rule in default.yaml first. And default.yaml will execute the abort{} method. And I find that the method will also abort the rule in mysql-slowsql.yaml (and other rules if exist).
The abort method is following:
```
    protected static final ThreadLocal<Binding> BINDING = ThreadLocal.withInitial(Binding::new);

    public void abort(final Closure<Void> cl) {
        BINDING.get().abort();
    }

    // BINDING.get().abort();
    public Binding abort() {
        setProperty(KEY_ABORT, true);
        return this;
    }
```
The reason of this bug is the BINDING is ThreadLoacal and OAP parse two rules in one thread.
I am confused about how to resolve it. May be we should use multiple threads to do these?

And now if the abort method is executed, other rules will not have chance to edit the status.
```
    public void sink(@DelegatesTo(SinkSpec.class) final Closure<?> cl) {
        if (BINDING.get().shouldAbort()) {
            return;
        }
        ...
```
It will directly return.

